	<Header validationStatus="Unknown" version="1.0" date="2026-07-15T00:00:00Z">
		<NoteSet>
			<Note>ST[14] Real-Time Forwarding Control. See pus_analysis/pus14.md and
				pus_simulator_architecture.md for the full design rationale.</Note>
			<Note>All forwarding-control logic (APFCC/HK FCC/Diag FCC tables, the shouldForward() gate,
				TC parsing, TM dump generation) lives on-board (emulated by Pus14Service in the
				simulator). This MDB only encodes the TC[14,x] configuration/dump-request commands and
				decodes the TM[14,4]/[14,8]/[14,12] dump reports -- it performs no filtering of its own.</Note>
			<Note>N2=0 (TC[14,1]/[14,2]) and N_structs=0 (TC[14,5]/[14,6]/[14,9]/[14,10]) mean
				"all services/structures for this APID" per spec convention; N3=0 means "all subtypes
				of this service type". TC[14,2]/[14,6]/[14,10] additionally have a zero-argument
				"empty the whole table" variant, since that request form has no N1 field -- a zero-byte
				payload is the runtime discriminator (checked in Pus14Service via bb.remaining()==0).</Note>
			<Note>HK FCC (TC[14,5-8]) and Diagnostic FCC (TC[14,9-12]) are maintained as pure
				bookkeeping in the simulator: ST[03] HK reports don't carry structure identifiers and
				ST[04] diagnostic reports don't exist in this simulator, so these two tables have no
				effect on which TM is actually forwarded (see pus14.md Gap 6).</Note>
			<Note>Default gate state is pass-all (an APID with no APFCC entry is forwarded), and PUS-1
				verification reports (type=1) and ST[14]'s own TM (type=14) always bypass the gate --
				this simulator uses a single fixed APID for all traffic, so a restrictive APFCC entry
				would otherwise block its own control channel.</Note>
		</NoteSet>
	</Header>
